{
  "answer": "**Kalpabuddha** describes the internalization of the five Tathāgatas (Vairocana, Akṣobhya, Ratnasambhava, Amitābha, Amoghasiddhi) within the practitioner's body, where they manifest as the five wisdoms (*pañcajñāna*: *śāśvatajñāna*, *ādarśajñāna*, *samatājñāna*/*ākāśamatājñāna*, *pratyavekṣaṇajñāna*, *kṛtyānuṣṭhānajñāna*) associated with the senses (eyes, ears, nose, mouth, heart). Its central claim is that, upon returning to their *lokadhātus*, these Tathāgatas reside in the body as the senses (*pañcendriya*), accompanied by their *devīs*, collectively forming the Divine Five-Souls (*Pañcātma*) that constitute the self (*ātman*). This realization of the *Pañcātma*—the \"supreme secret\"—is presented as the text's culminating insight.[^1][^2]\n\n**San Hyan Mahājñāna** (\"The Sacred Supreme Wisdom\") expounds a hierarchical progression of consciousness states (*avasthās*): *jāgrat* (waking), *svapna* (dreaming), *suṣupti* (deep sleep), *tūrya* (fourth state), *tūryānta*, *kaivalya* (isolation), and *paramakaivalya* (supreme isolation), mapped to bodily loci (navel, heart, throat, forehead, hand, head), colors, deities (from Brahmā to Paramaśiva), and *yugas*. Its central claim is that *mahājñāna* reveals Śiva/Paramashiva as the ultimate reality (*paramakaivalya*), abiding in the *ātma-liṅga* and \"void within the void\" at the heart's apex—a qualityless, eternal, formless *mokṣa* beyond manifestation (*vyakta*) and unmanifest (*avyakta*), accessed via *oṃkāra*, breath control, and guru-upadeśa.[^3]\n\nThese texts do not name the identical end-state. *Kalpabuddha*'s Buddhist tantric terminus—the embodied *pañcajñāna* as *Pañcātma*—resembles a preparatory integration of wisdoms and subtle-body principles, akin to a \"milestone\" in *San Hyan Mahājñāna*'s Shaiva schema. There, *kaivalya*/*kevala* (pure isolation) is an penultimate state preceding *paramakaivalya*, the non-dual void-Shiva beyond deity-multiplicities or body-localizations.[^4] No corpus evidence equates the two directly; *Kalpabuddha* lacks *kevala-jñāna* phrasing, treating fivefold wisdom as final, while *San Hyan* transcends such structures.\n\n[^1]: *Kalpabuddha*, Chapter 6, [paragraph](/works/unknown-kalpabuddha-d760dc/06/translation/#p-c8567e).\n\n[^2]: *Kalpabuddha*, Chapters 1–5, e.g., [Chapter 1, paragraph](/works/unknown-kalpabuddha-d760dc/01/translation/#p-e1c8df); [Chapter 2, paragraph](/works/unknown-kalpabuddha-d760dc/02/translation/#p-5a580a).\n\n[^3]: *San Hyan Mahājñāna*, Chapter 1, [paragraphs](/works/unknown-san-hyan-mahajnana-11c531/01/translation/#p-9194a6) (kaivalya/*paramakaivalya* as \"seven skies\"); [paragraph](/works/unknown-san-hyan-mahajnana-11c531/01/translation/#p-f7e6ce) (Śiva in void); [paragraph](/works/unknown-san-hyan-mahajnana-11c531/01/translation/#p-ad1274) (*jñānasandhi* as mokṣa).\n\n[^4]: *San Hyan Mahājñāna*, Chapter 1, [paragraph](/works/unknown-san-hyan-mahajnana-11c531/01/translation/#p-c25d64) (progression to *paramakaivalya*). No *kewala-jñāna*/*kevala-jñāna* in *Kalpabuddha*; nearest corpus hit is *kevalaśuddha* (pure isolation) as a *Gaṇapatitattva* liberation stage ([paragraph](/works/unknown-ganapatitattva-66a136/01/translation/#p-dd5818)).",
